of constructing a mixed-use development containing 90 residential apartment units and

On Tuesday, April 5, 2016, the Applicant met with the City of Beverly Parking and Traffic
Commission to review the results of a Traffic Impact and Access Study prepared for the
project dated March 28, 2016. During this meeting, residents expressed concern for the
potential increase in cut-through traffic on Lenox Street that could result from the project.
Although the layout of the driveways and location of the site are anticipated to result in
negligible traffic increases on Lenox Street, TEC has performed this sensitivity analysis to
evaluate the impacts of the proposed development on traffic operations along Lenox Street.
Lenox Street is a one-way east-west local roadway connecting Cabot Street to the east and
Rantoul Street (Route 1A) to the west. The roadway is 26-feet wide curb-to-curb with on-
street parking permitted on the northerly side of the roadway. Although a one-way
roadway, there is currently no signage to indicate the one-way flow characteristics at the
intersection of Cabot Street / Lenox Street / Pickett Street. Although “One-Way” and “Do
Not Enter” signage is present at the intersection of Rantoul Street / Lenox Street, the
existing signs are bent and loose from the sign post. The signage is also not visible to
vehicles attempting a right-turn onto Lenox Street from Rantoul Street northbound. In
addition, the directional application for Google Maps and GPS systems will direct vehicles the

As shown in Table 1, Lenox Street experiences approximately one vehicle every two to four
minutes exiting onto Rantoul Street during the weekday morning and evening peak hours.
Slightly less than half of this traffic volume represents cut-through traffic. Nearly all of this
cut-through traffic was observed entering Lenox Street via Pickett Street, due to the
availability of other cross-streets between Rantoul Street and Cabot Street further north and
south of Lenox Street. The majority of cut-through traffic exits left from Lenox Street to

text.b: Potential for Increase in Cut-Through Trips

page.text: Due to the configuration of the site driveways and the location of the site south of Lenox
Street, the proposed redevelopment project is anticipated to result in negligible increases in
traffic on Lenox Street. The one-way traffic flow on Lenox Street would limit any site-
generated trips using Lenox Street to entering trips only. Because the entrance driveway will
be located at the southerly end of the site, vehicles using Lenox Street would have to turn
left onto Rantoul Street, then right into the site driveway to access the site. As such, anyone
traveling to the site from locations along Cabot Street south of Summer Street would be
back-tracking and extending travel time and distance by utilizing Lenox Street. Therefore, all
site-generated trips from locations south of Summer Street are anticipated to utilize other
cross streets further south to access Rantoul Street to the site.
In addition, any site-generated trips from the north on Cabot Street would pass by Rantoul
Street to access Lenox Street. Therefore, all site-generated trips from locations north and
west of Rantoul Street along Cabot Street are anticipated to utilize Rantoul Street to access
The only reasonable draw for site-generated trips traveling to the site to utilize Lenox Street
as a cut-through route would be for local trips from the neighborhoods bordered by Odell
Avenue, Essex Street, and Columbus Avenue. As the majority of this area is residential in
nature, and there is limited draw for trips between residential-to-residential land uses, the
volume of site-generated trips utilizing Lenox Street as a cut-through route will be negligible.

traffic exiting Lenox Street. The analysis for the STOP-controlled unsignalized intersection of

TEC, Inc. (TEC) has been retained by Windover Development (the “Applicant”) to prepare a
Traffic Impact and Access Study (TIAS) for the redevelopment of the property located at #480-
#482 Rantoul Street (Parcels 20-107 and 20-108) in Beverly, Massachusetts. The site was
formerly occupied by a Friendly’s Restaurant and is currently vacant. The project consists of
constructing a mixed-use development containing 90 residential apartment units and
1,900 square feet (SF) of specialty retail space. Access to the site is proposed along the
westerly side of Rantoul Street (Route 1A) via an entrance-only driveway at the southerly edge
of the site and an exit-only driveway at the northerly edge of the site.
TEC has evaluated the traffic operations for the site driveways and study area intersections
under existing and future conditions. The future year planning horizon examines traffic
operations under existing conditions (2016) as well as a 7-year design horizon (2023) for traffic-
volume projections, which includes an evaluation of the No-Build conditions (without the
proposed project) and Build conditions (with site traffic added). These conditions are compared
to determine what, if any, additional off-site mitigation is necessary to provide reasonable traffic
operations in the area after the project is complete.

Rantoul Street, signed as Massachusetts Route 1A, is a two-lane, north-south principal arterial
roadway maintained by the City of Beverly in the vicinity of the Project site. The roadway
provides regional connections along the North Shore, paralleling the shoreline. Locally,
Route 1A provides connection between the Town of Wenham to the north and the City of Salem
to the south, with Rantoul Street terminating at Cabot Street on either end. Rantoul Street is
generally ±45-feet wide, with auxiliary turning lanes at the signalized intersections and on-

Rantoul Street is 25 miles-per-hour (MPH). Land uses along Rantoul Street are primarily

Cabot Street, signed as Massachusetts Route 1A west of Rantoul Street and Massachusetts

of the study area is separated by a marked centerline. The posted speed limit along Cabot
Street is 30 MPH. Land uses along Cabot Street are generally commercial and residential in

TEC, Inc. visited the site on Monday, March 7, 2016 to measure the available sight distances at
the proposed site driveways. The available sight distances were compared to minimum
requirements established by the American Association of State Highway and Transportation
Sight distance represents the length of roadway that is visible to a driver traveling within the
roadway. Two types of sight distance are typically evaluated for driveways and intersections:
stopping sight distance (SSD) and intersection sight distance (ISD). SSD is the minimum
distance required for a driver traveling along a roadway to perceive an object in the roadway
and stop safely in advance of the object when traveling on a wet pavement surface. SSD is
measured from an eye height of 3.5 feet to an object height of two (2) feet above the ground,
which is equivalent to a driver viewing the taillight of a vehicle ahead. SSD is measured along
the centerline of the travel lane approaching the driveway or intersection.
ISD represents the length of the roadway visible to a driver waiting to exit a driveway or minor
street. Minimum ISD requirements are based on the distance required for a driver to exit a
minor street onto a major street without requiring an approaching vehicle to reduce its speed
from the design speed to less than 70 percent of the design speed. ISD is measured from an
eye height of 3.5 feet to an object height of 3.5 feet, and is measured from a distance 15 feet
off the edge of the travel-way of the major roadway to represent a driver waiting to exit a
SSD is typically considered the critical sight distance, as it represents the minimum distance
required for safe stopping, while ISD represents an acceptable speed reduction for approaching
vehicles. The ISD, however, must be at least equal to the minimum required SSD in order to
prevent a driver from entering the roadway when an approaching vehicle is too close to safely
stop. The guidance provided by AASHTO states:
“If the available sight distance for an entering or crossing vehicle is at least equal to the
appropriate stopping sight distance for the major road, then drivers have sufficient
sight distance to anticipate and avoid collisions. However, in some cases, this may
require a major-road vehicle to stop or slow to accommodate the maneuver by a minor-
road vehicle. To enhance traffic operations, intersection sight distances that exceed
stopping sight distances are desirable along the major road.”

Traffic volumes in the study area were projected to the year 2023, which reflects a seven-year
planning horizon per MassDOT standards. The traffic conditions for the year 2023, under No-
Build conditions, were developed to document the operating conditions independent of the
proposed project, including all existing traffic, new traffic resulting from background growth,
and traffic from specific development projects expected to be completed by 2023. Anticipated
site-generated traffic volumes for the proposed residential development were superimposed
upon the No-Build traffic networks to reflect the Build conditions with the proposed project.
Traffic growth is a function of the expected land development in the immediate area and the
surrounding region. Several methods can be used to estimate this growth. Traffic engineers
frequently employ an annual percentage increase in traffic growth, which is applied to all traffic
volumes under study. The drawback to such a procedure is that some turning volumes may
actually grow at either a higher or a lower rate at particular intersections.
An alternative procedure identifies the location and type of planned development, estimates the
traffic to be generated, and assigns it to the area roadway network. This procedure produces a
more realistic estimate of growth for local traffic. However, the drawback of this procedure is
that the potential growth in population and development external to the study area would not
be accounted for in the traffic projections.
To provide a conservative analysis framework, both procedures were considered.
Traffic-volume data compiled by MassDOT from permanent count stations and historic traffic
along local roadways within the vicinity of the project were reviewed in
order to determine traffic growth trends. Based on the MassDOT traffic volume data, traffic
volumes in the area have been decreasing at a rate of 1.0 percent per year since 2004.
Therefore, to provide a conservative (worse-case) analysis scenario, a 1.0 percent per year
compounded annual background traffic growth rate was used to account for potential future
traffic growth external to the study area and presently unforeseen development. Count station
data have been included in Attachment F.

A primary result of capacity analyses is the assignment of levels-of-service to traffic facilities
The concept of level-of-service is defined as a qualitative
measure describing operational conditions within a traffic stream and their perception by motor-
ists and/or passengers. A level-of-service definition provides an index to quality of traffic flow
in terms of such factors as speed, travel time, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, com-
Six levels-of-service are defined for each type of facility. They are given letter designations
from A to F, with level-of-service (LOS) A representing the best operating conditions and
subsequent letters representing decreasing operation conditions. Since the level-of-service of a
traffic facility is a function of the traffic flows placed upon it, such a facility may operate at a
wide range of levels-of-service, depending on the time of day, day of week, or period of year.

Mathematically, control delay is a function of the capacity and degree of saturation of the lane
group and/or approach under study and is a quantification of motorist delay associated with
traffic control devices such as traffic signals and STOP signs. Control delay includes the effects
of initial deceleration delay approaching a STOP sign, stopped delay, queue move-up time, and
final acceleration delay from a stopped condition. Definitions for level-of-service at unsignalized

The City of Beverly Zoning By-Laws contains off-street parking supply requirements for
residential and retail land uses as defined in Section 38-25(A). For residential land uses within
the Central Business District, the zoning ordinance requires that 1 space per residential unit for
residential units of 1 bedroom or smaller and 2 spaces per residential unit with 2 or more
bedrooms. For retail land uses, 1 space per 275 square feet is required for establishments
As part of the project, the Proponent proposes to construct 118 parking spaces on-site to
accommodate the residential apartment units. A total of 28 two-bedroom and 62 one-bedroom
apartment units will be provided, requiring a total of 118 parking spaces to satisfy City of
Beverly Zoning Ordinances. Therefore, the proposed parking supply will satisfy City of Beverly
Zoning Ordinance for the residential apartments on site.
Retail parking is expected to occur on-street. Under Section 38-25(A)(2)(b) of the City of
Beverly Zoning Ordinances, the parking spaces for non-residential uses may be provided off-site
in a public parking facility located within 500 feet or within any on-street parking spaces located
within the frontage of the property. A total of seven on-street parking spaces may be
accommodated on the westerly side of Rantoul Street (Route 1A), along the site frontage,
which will be adequate to satisfy City of Beverly Zoning Ordinances for the proposed retail
The proposed residential and retail land uses are anticipated to generate peak parking demands
at varying times of the day, allowing for sharing of parking spaces on the site between the
residential and retail uses. For example, a space that is occupied by a tenant at night may be
utilized by a retail customer during the day. TEC estimated the site-generated parking demand
based on standard parking rates published in the ITE publication
for LUC 221 – Low/Mid-Rise Apartment and LUC 820 – Shopping Center. The parking
demand generated during each hour of the day was estimated for each land use separately and
superimposed with the hourly parking demand generated by each of the remaining land uses to
estimate the total hourly parking demand throughout an average weekday and Saturday.
Based on the ITE data for the proposed land uses, a peak parking demand of 108 parking
spaces is estimated for the proposed retail and apartments on a weekday, and a peak parking
demand of 93 parking spaces is estimated on a Saturday. A total of 118 parking spaces will be
provided on the site. Therefore, the proposed parking supply will be adequate to accommodate
the peak parking demand generated by the proposed redevelopment. A detailed breakdown of
the peak parking demand data is provided in Attachment K.
